title: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances

heading_context: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
chunks.html_content:
You need to report changes to your circumstances so you keep getting the right amount of benefits.

Your claim might be stopped or reduced if you do not report a change straight away or you give incorrect information.
chunks.plain_content:
Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
You need to report changes to your circumstances so you keep getting the right amount of benefits.
Your claim might be stopped or reduced if you do not report a change straight away or you give incorrect information.

heading_context: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
chunks.plain_content:
Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
This page is also available in Welsh (Cymraeg).

heading_context: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
chunks.html_content: If you do not report a change or a mistake, you might be paid too much. If you are, you might have to pay some of the money back. You might also have to pay a 50 penalty.
chunks.plain_content:
Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
If you do not report a change or a mistake, you might be paid too much. If you are, you might have to pay some of the money back. You might also have to pay a 50 penalty.

heading_context: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
chunks.html_content: If you deliberately do not report changes, youre committing benefit fraud.
chunks.plain_content:
Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
If you deliberately do not report changes, youre committing benefit fraud.

heading_context: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
chunks.html_content:
Changes can include:

  • changing your name or gender
  • finding or finishing a job, or working different hours
  • your income going up or down
  • starting or stopping education, training or an apprenticeship
  • moving house
  • people moving into or out of the place you live (for example your partner, a child or lodger)
  • the death of your partner or someone you live with
  • having a baby
  • starting or stopping caring for someone
  • getting married or divorced
  • starting or ending a civil partnership
  • planning to go abroad for any length of time
  • going into hospital, a care home or sheltered accommodation

  • any changes to your medical condition or disability

  • changing your doctor

  • changes to your pension, savings, investments or property

  • changes to other money you get (for example student loans or grants, sick pay or money you get from a charity)

  • changes to the benefits you or anyone else in your house gets

  • you or your partner getting back-pay (sometimes called arrears) for salary or earnings youre owed
  • changes to your immigration status, if youre not a British citizen

heading_context: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
chunks.html_content: If you claim Child Benefit you also need to report changes to your childs circumstances.
chunks.plain_content:

Changes you need to report
If you claim Child Benefit you also need to report changes to your childs circumstances.

heading_context: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
chunks.html_content: Use the Tell Us Once service if someone dies when theyre receiving benefits. The process is different if youre in Northern Ireland.
chunks.plain_content:
Benefits: report a change in your circumstances

Reporting a death

heading_context: Benefits: report a change in your circumstances
chunks.html_content:
Who you tell depends on which benefits you get. Youll need to report your change to more than one organisation if you get more than one benefit.

Report changes using your Universal Credit online account if you have one or contact the Universal Credit helpline.

  • Personal Independence Payment (PIP).
